  <li id="comment-42186" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Nancy Love</cite></div>
      <a href="index.html?p=62#comment-42186"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2014-11-07T21:36:25-05:00">Friday, November 7, 2014 at 9:36 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I had the privilege of being a student in Molly&#39;s class @ Quartz Mountain, and it was a joy from start to finish.</p>
<p>As a teacher, Molly was well prepared and her writing assignments thought provoking. The thing that struck me most, however, was her generosity as a working artist. The class generally, was composed of all women (with the exception of one gentleman named Bill!) and I would describe us as an enthusiastic group of students who ENJOY writing but haven&#39;t earned the distinction of using the word &#8220;writer&#8221; &#8211; much less with a capital &#8220;W&#8221; &#8211; to describe ourselves. And yet, Molly was kind, gracious and respectful.</p>
<p>We wanted bits and pieces of her time individually &#8211; which can be exhausting when you&#39;re both instructor and facilitator &#8211; yet she worked us in on breaks and over meals. I watched her from across the room at dinner a couple of evenings, and she was engaging and generous with each student as if she was having a lively conversation with Virginia Woolf! It reminded me of a time I had the pleasure of being present when Yo-Yo Ma was rehearsing a piece he would perform later that night. The audience at the rehearsal was about 100 orchestra kids from local public schools, and me. Following his rehearsal, he hopped off of the stage to greet any student who wanted to meet him and talk about playing in an orchestra (he also let them play his Stradivarius cello which was stunning.)</p>
<p>I was struck by his generosity and the brilliance of his actions (which went on for nearly 2 hours!) and I thought to myself, &#8220;I&#39;ve just gotten a front-row seat to the generosity of a remarkable man.&#8221;</p>
<p>Yo-Yo Ma didn&#39;t have to do that for those kids, and neither did Molly have to spend all of her free time listening to us, yet she did because that&#39;s who Molly is &#8211; a good and decent person (who is also immensely talented!)</p>
<p>Thank you, Molly, for the front-row seat to writing, the creative process and generosity. All week I&#39;ve been fueled from my Molly inspiration and riding Pegasus ever since!</p>
    </div>

